{{Use dmy dates|date=May 2015}} {{Use British English|date=May 2015}} {{Infobox television | show_name = The Brits Who Built the Modern World | image = | caption = | show_name_2 = | genre = Factual | creator = | based_on = | developer = | writer = Peter Sweasey | director = Peter Sweasey | starring = | theme_music_composer = | opentheme = | endtheme = | composer = | country = United Kingdom | language = English | num_series = 1 | num_episodes = 3 | list_episodes = #Episode list | executive_producer = Nicholas Kent | producer = Peter Sweasey | editor = | location = | cinematography = | camera = | runtime = | company = | distributor = | channel = {{Plainlist | *[[BBC Four]] *[[BBC Four HD]] }} | picture_format = [[16:9]] [[1080i]] | audio_format = [[Stereophonic sound|Stereo]] | first_aired = {{Start date|2014|2|13|df=yes}} | last_aired = {{End date|2014|2|27|df=yes}} | preceded_by = | followed_by = | related = | website = http://www.bbc.co.uk/programmes/b03vgz7r | production_website = }}
'''''The Brits Who Built the Modern World''''' is a British factual television series that was first broadcast on [[BBC Four]] from 13 to 27 February 2014. The three-part series tells the story of British architects [[Richard Rogers]], [[Norman Foster]], [[Nicholas Grimshaw]], [[Michael Hopkins (architect)|Michael Hopkins]] and [[Terry Farrell (architect)|Terry Farrell]].<ref name=indyhopkinshouse>{{cite news | url=https://www.independent.co.uk/arts-entertainment/architecture/the-brits-who-built-the-modern-world-and-49b--the-house-built-by-high-tech-designers-michael-and-patty-hopkins-8950228.html | title=The Brits Who Built the Modern World and 49b - the house built by High Tech designers Michael and Patty Hopkins | work=The Independent | date=19 November 2013 | accessdate=8 February 2014 | author=Merrick, Jay}}</ref>
==Production== The series was produced with the [[Open University]] and a [[Royal Institute of British Architects]] exhibition<ref>{{cite news | url=http://www.televisual.com/news-detail/BBC-Four-to-run-season-on-architecture_nid-3852.html | title=BBC Four to run season on architecture | work=Televisual | date=4 February 2014 | accessdate=8 February 2014 | author=Considine, Pippa}}</ref><ref>{{cite news | url=http://www.bbc.co.uk/mediacentre/latestnews/2014/nation-builders-release.html | title=BBC Four celebrates architecture with Nation Builders season | work=BBC | date=3 February 2014 | accessdate=8 February 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite news | url=http://www.construction-manager.co.uk/news/bbc-highlights-brits-who-built-modern-world/ | title=BBC highlights the Brits who Build the Modern World | work=Construction Manager | date=6 February 2014 | accessdate=8 February 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.open.edu/openlearn/whats-on/tv/ou-on-the-bbc-the-brits-who-built-the-modern-world | title=OU on the BBC: The Brits Who Built The Modern World | work=Open University | date=3 February 2014 | accessdate=8 February 2014}}</ref> (which also included Lady [[Patty Hopkins]]).<ref name=indyhopkinshouse /> The exhibition was open between 13 February and 27 May 2014.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.architecture.com/WhatsOn/RIBAPublicProgramme/brits-who-built-the-modern-world/brits.aspx | title=The Brits Who Built The Modern World | work=RIBA | accessdate=8 February 2014}}</ref>
==Episode list== {| class="wikitable plainrowheaders" style="background:#FFFFFF;" !style="background: #bfe0bf;"| # !style="background: #bfe0bf;"| Title !style="background: #bfe0bf;"| Directed by !style="background: #bfe0bf;"| Written by !style="background: #bfe0bf;"| Original air date |- {{Episode list |EpisodeNumber=1 |Title=The Freedom of the Future |DirectedBy=Peter Sweasey |WrittenBy=Peter Sweasey |OriginalAirDate={{Start date|2014|2|13|df=yes}} |ShortSummary= |LineColor=bfe0bf }} {{Episode list |EpisodeNumber=2 |Title=The Power of the Past |DirectedBy=Peter Sweasey |WrittenBy=Peter Sweasey |OriginalAirDate={{Start date|2014|2|20|df=yes}} |ShortSummary= |LineColor=bfe0bf }} {{Episode list |EpisodeNumber=3 |Title=The Politics of Power |DirectedBy=Peter Sweasey |WrittenBy=Peter Sweasey |OriginalAirDate={{Start date|2014|2|27|df=yes}} |ShortSummary= |LineColor=bfe0bf }} |}
==Controversy== The series was the subject of controversy when the BBC were accused of removing Patty Hopkins from a photograph of the architects, used to illustrate the third programme of the series. Patty Hopkins had been a full partner in the Hopkins company from the outset. The BBC were accused of ignoring women architects, though the BBC responded by saying that at the start of making the series, the director met with both Michael and Patricia Hopkins to discuss their involvement in the series.<ref>{{cite news|author=Richard Waite, Laura Mark |title=BBC slammed for ‘bias’ after Patty Hopkins is sidelined in TV show |url=http://www.architectsjournal.co.uk/news/bbc-slammed-for-bias-after-patty-hopkins-is-sidelined-in-tv-show/8659720.article |work=[[The Architects' Journal]] |date=5 March 2014 |accessdate=23 October 2015 |quote= Deborah Saunt co-founder of DSDHA, said: ‘'''''The point is that the BBC are publicising the work of these great British architects without including a very important sixth member (being a full partner in Hopkins Architects from the beginning) - a member who was present at the time when the group photo was taken! To knowingly choose to use a metaphorically or literally [[photoshopped|edited photo]] without Patty in it, is an outrage.'''''' }}</ref>
